Beyonce was right. This isn't country music, it's Beyonce music.  Country music originated in what is now West Virginia, by people who came to this country as indentured servants and who cut their part of VA off from the rest of the state because they refused to fight in a war being fought for what some southerners thought was their "right" to own slaves. Indentured servants got a taste of that and weren't going to support it.  Sorry to the African-Americans who claim to be the originators of country music, you're wrong. AA's originated rhythm  and blues and there are country songs that have heavy rhythm and blues influence in them, but they are not the whole of country music, nor are they it's origins. You have to look to ballads from the isles of Scotland and Ireland, from whence came most of those indentured servants, to find the beginnings of American country music. You'll have to look into the 1930s, 40s 50s and 60s for true American country music anyway, because it's long gone. Beyonce is great at singing & always will be & was also great here too, but she didn't wear a country style cowboy hat & I didn't hear a country accent twang in her voice in this song here. Country was at it's roots a black genre. Few know that. It started with what is now either called rhythm and blues or bluegrass. One day long before Dolly Parton or Patsy Cline someone went up into the Appalachians and heard the music there (which was white hillbilly) then they went to the Louisiana bayou and heard the African Americans there and they immitated the two styles and started the bare roots of what we came to know as country. And knowing this bit of music history I've always wondered why there hasn't been more African Americans in the genre. You go Beyonce for reclaiming a bit back.

Can people please stop pretending that black people created country music? country music comes from FOLK music, which existed way before the US was even founded. Folk music comes from the German word "volk". Country music, jazz, rock, bluegrass, psychobilly, rockabilly; all these genres stem from FOLK music. SOME of those genres (country, jazz, blues) are products of black AND white people collaborating, creating beautiful things TOGETHER, yet the foundations of country come from folk music, created by white people. To overlook the contributions of either demographic to those genres is unfair.  Plus, the foundations of musical theory were laid way before the US was founded. Not one instrument used to play jazz, country, bluegrass, rock, or country was created by black people, all those instruments were created by Germans, Spaniards, and Italians. FACT. There are black cowboys and cowgirls, but Beyonce isn't one of them.  Not everybody from Houston is a cowgirl or a fan of country. If her country music was good tho, that would be one thing. But why does she feel it's necessary to morph into a white woman to release a country album. Her skin is way lighter than ever before (like Oprah, lil Kim, Nicki Minaj), she lives in straight blonde wigs.  It's def giving appropriation, and that Texas hold em song is straight up trash ğŸ˜†ğŸ—‘ï¸ "Ultimately, country music's roots lie in the ballads, folk songs, and popular songs of the English, Scots, and Irish settlers of the Appalachians and other parts of the South." " In essence, country is one part of folk. It is a unique style of folk music. Folk musicâ€”even in its second waveâ€”didn't stray from its pure form." "Country music has a rich and diverse history that spans over a century, evolving from the traditional folk music of the Southern United States". "Country Music emerged as British Isles settlers moved into the Appalachians. A fusion of English fiddle music, Scots-Irish dance music & American blues."  It's extremely disrespectful (and borderline racist) to overlook and exclude the contributions white people made to  the foundations of musical theory in general and folk, country, rock, blues, etc.

Great B! Pushing the boundaries, thatâ€™s what legends do. They call Elvis the King of Rock and Roll, but from before the 1920â€™s Black music was appropriated and ultimately credited to white musicians.  Whether you call it Blues, Rock, Country, R&B, Soul, almost all of it started out as a style of music played by Black American artists. Robert Johnson, Muddy Waters, Howlin Wolf, Lead Belly, Ella Fitzgerald, Nina Simone, Chuck Berry, Louis Armstrong, Aretha Franklin, Billie Holliday, Otis Redding, Ray Charles. Those are just some the musicians who created the styles of music we listen to even today. Even much of that music started out as Spirituals sung by slaves in the fields. That music inspired Buddy Holly, Elvis, The Beatles, Led Zeppelin, The Clash, Johnny Cash, Waylon Jennings, Aerosmith, Justin Timberlake, Chris Stapleton, etc. That it is why it is great to see BeyoncÃ©, Stevie Wonder, Prince, Jimi Hendrix, Whitney Houston, Alecia Keys, etc. continue to expand on the massive influence that Black Americans have contributed to essentially every type of popular music we listen to in the US.

The only reason 'What You Get...' wasn't categorized as a country song, when Tina Turner (her record co) released it, back in the 80s, ..is the issue of Ms. Turner's race. I've read it described as "country-flavored" or "tinged" or some other nonsense, as if the critic was doing Ms. Turner a kindness - utter BS! You've got to be hearing-impaired or dead not to hear and know what kind of music, TT was performing in 'What You Get...'. If Dolly Pardon [Love Dolly Pardon...nothing against her.] or some other white country music artist had performed 'What You Get...', without changing a single chord, it would have been billed 'country music', and how well or poorly it performed would have been its own consideration. Irrespective of how entertaining her two NEW songs are, it's a similarly motivated cultural quirk that now follows Beyonce's foray into country music. If we're being fair [Ha!], ..the only issue or question we should have with 'Texas Hold'em', after acknowledging its country music DNA, is - is the damn thing any good? Country music, blue grass music, and rock and roll music WERE ALL CREATED BY BLACK PEOPLE.  But most (white) Americans donâ€™t know that.  Elvis Presley knew to a certain extent. He gave an interview once and when asked about rock and roll he talked about how it came from black people and being around black people when he was a kid was when he first heard it when they performed it.  I watched a documentary on the roots of those genres of music and that is how I learned that information.
Yes, rock 'n' roll has deep roots in African American music traditions and can be considered a genre that originated from black music. It emerged in the United States in the late 1940s and early 1950s, drawing heavily from African American genres such as blues, R&B (Rhythm and Blues), gospel, and jazz. These musical forms, characterized by their use of the blues scale, call and response patterns, and distinctive rhythms, were foundational to the development of rock 'n' roll.  Artists like Chuck Berry, Little Richard, Fats Domino, and Sister Rosetta Tharpe were among the pioneers of rock 'n' roll, contributing significantly to its sound, style, and evolution. Their work not only influenced the genre directly but also paved the way for subsequent generations of rock musicians of all backgrounds.  While rock 'n' roll would grow to encompass a wide range of influences and subgenres, with artists and audiences of diverse racial and ethnic backgrounds, its origins as a genre fundamentally tied to African American music and culture are clear. The contributions of black musicians have been essential to the development of rock 'n' roll, marking it as a genre that originated within black music traditions.
ğŸ–¤ğŸµğŸ¼ğŸ¶ğŸ’ğŸ’¯
The origins of country music are complex and multifaceted, drawing from various musical traditions. It's not accurate to categorize country music as originally "black music" in a simplistic way; however, African American musicians have played a significant and often underrecognized role in the development of the genre. The roots of country music can be traced to the folk music of various groups, including European immigrants (especially from the British Isles) and African Americans, in the rural regions of the Southern United States.  African American influences are particularly notable in the development of country music through the blues, which significantly impacted the genre's instrumental and vocal styles. The banjo, for example, an instrument central to early country music, has African origins. Moreover, the exchange of musical ideas between black and white musicians in the South contributed to the formation of the country genre.  In the early 20th century, as country music began to emerge as a distinct genre, African American contributions continued to be vital but were often marginalized or not as prominently recognized as those of white musicians. Despite this, black artists like DeFord Bailey, a pioneer harmonica player, made significant contributions to the genre. Bailey was among the first stars of the Grand Ole Opry, a key institution in country music.  Over the decades, the lines between genres have continued to blur, with artists from various backgrounds drawing inspiration from and contributing to the country music tradition. While country music has been predominantly marketed to and associated with white audiences, its origins are indeed multicultural, reflecting a complex interplay of influences that includes significant contributions from African American music and culture.

16 Carriages is whacked out bad and a poor attempt to traverse country music from R&B but this song follows the horse bangs of Daddy Lessons. This one's a good country, been a country fan since 2008. This song has something that 16 Carriages lack, the confidence, the successful attempt, though both are lyrically good. It doesn't have the casual (yet effective) narrative style of the state-of-the-art country songs but it still works. Not as good as those recently released by Zach Bryan, or Golden Hour by Kacey Musgraves, or Speak Now by Taylor Swift, or even the first four albums of Chris Stapleton or Dolly Parton's and Shania Twain's music but it still works, and is working effectively. This is brilliant!!
The modern banjo derives from instruments that have been recorded to be in use in North America and the Caribbean since the 17th century by enslaved people taken from West and Central Africa. Their African-style instruments were crafted from split gourds with animal skins stretched across them. Strings, from gut or vegetable fibers, were attached to a wooden neck. Written references to the banjo in North America and the Caribbean appear in the 17th and 18th centuries. Happy Black History Month!

Who else here before 1 million???
This is so significant for a mega star like Beyonce to do this. While there are few African American music artists that have made headway into country and old veterans like the late Charley Pride,  most don't know the roots of African Americans and country.  Growing up, I  just thought it was white folks music and culture because it was never played at my house or by other Black people.  My dad loved watching cowboy movies, who at the time were mostly portrayed as white men, which just further confirmed what I thought. In high school when I became president of FFA (Future Farmers of America), I was the only Black officier, and the white officers and members  always dressed  with cowboy and cowgirl aesthetics. I never did because I had never notice Black people wearing such clothes where I'm from, even though I was living in the country.  During the state rally competition, I swept all categories from public speaking to meat judging and was headed to nationals. It wasn't until I talk to my grandpa that I learned a little bit of history.  He ask me did I have my cowboy outfit ready for nationals. I said hell no ; Black people don't wear that stuff. He said, who told you that. I told him  I had never notice anyone wearing it. He got up and show me some old pictures of him and his friends with their cowboy hats, jeans, ties, big silver belt buckle and boots. I was floored. and then he told me about all the Black people that had migrated west and started settlements that were sometime overrrun by whites if they were doing well. He then took me shopping to by me an outfit. I asked him why did he nor my dad tell me. He said because I didn't ask and to them it wasn't important.  They were to busy trying to survive and put food on the table. It's good to see Beyonce do this to continue to reclaim Black history. Even though she is far from the first,  the star power she brings is important.  From blues trail ride music, country music, old historic Black western settlements like Nicodemus, KS,  and  finally to black Cowboy movies finally being made, it is long overdue for the historical connections between African Americans and country to be reveal. It has never been White only.
